{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01AdMaHnLetyzPsyHZTGwMaq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I see the key piece. At line 42:\n```go\nNamespaceSelector: clusterPodPlacementConfig.Spec.NamespaceSelector,\n```\n\nThe `NamespaceSelector` from the CPPC is set on the actual mutating webhook's `NamespaceSelector` field. In the test environment, the webhook configuration in `getMutatingWebHook()` doesn't have a `NamespaceSelector`, so all namespaces are covered by the webhook.\n\nBut in the test, the CPPC created in BeforeSuite doesn't have a `NamespaceSelector` either. So the test's question is: with the current code logic, will a pod in `openshift-kube-apiserver` get the scheduling gate?\n\nLooking at `shouldIgnorePod`:\n```go\nreturn utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace || strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\") || ...\n```\n\n`openshift-kube-apiserver` does NOT start with `kube-`, so this wouldn't be caught. But wait — is the NAMESPACE env var set in tests? Let me check.\n\nThe `utils.Namespace()` returns the NAMESPACE env var, which defaults to `\"default\"`. In the test, it would be `\"default\"` unless changed.\n\nSo a pod in `openshift-kube-apiserver` would indeed get the scheduling gate based on current code — unless there's something else I'm missing. Let me check the production webhook setup code."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":987,"cache_read_input_tokens":63596,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":987,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1b396984-548a-4426-a66f-ae630d9417f5","uuid":"d36aa65f-67d2-41f3-a064-4cab324f93a2","timestamp":"2026-07-16T13:42:38.803Z","request_id":"req_vrtx_011Cd5qKNnijLuuysdmhXtCY"}
