{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01VwQ9Qfn2uWJq2L9pNR7wiH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I see: the production webhook sets `NamespaceSelector` from `clusterPodPlacementConfig.Spec.NamespaceSelector`. When the CPPC has a namespaceSelector matching all namespaces (e.g., `{}`), the webhook fires for all namespaces. But `shouldIgnorePod` still checks `strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\")`.\n\n`openshift-kube-apiserver` does NOT start with `kube-`, so based on `shouldIgnorePod`, it would NOT be ignored. But the task says to test that it IS excluded (NOT assigned the scheduling gate). \n\nLet me re-read the task: \"a pod created in the namespace openshift-kube-apiserver is NOT assigned the scheduling gate, even when ClusterPodPlacementConfig has a namespaceSelector that matches all namespaces.\"\n\nThis is an integration test. In the test environment, the webhook fires for all namespaces (no namespaceSelector on the webhook config). The question is: does the webhook Handler code exclude `openshift-kube-apiserver`?\n\nLooking at the Handle function, it calls `shouldIgnorePod`. For `openshift-kube-apiserver`:\n- `utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace` → false (unless NAMESPACE is set to `openshift-kube-apiserver`)\n- `strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\")` → false (starts with `openshift-`)\n- Other checks also won't apply for a simple pod\n\nSo the pod WOULD get the scheduling gate. But the task asks to test that it does NOT. This suggests there might be additional logic I'm missing, OR the task is asking us to write a test that will currently fail, OR I need to look more carefully.\n\nLet me check if there's namespace-level exclusion logic I've missed."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1636,"cache_read_input_tokens":64583,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1636,"ephemeral_1h_input_toke